    dek: `The safety-first mindset from Chapter 1 becomes real through one simple, repeatable habit: the safety meeting. It's a two-minute briefing that turns "be careful" into a specific, shared plan — and it's the single most effective safety tool a small production has.`,
    seoTitle: "The Film Set Safety Meeting: How to Run One | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to run a film set safety meeting and build safety into your call sheet — the daily briefing, safety notes, nearest hospital, and emergency contacts. Chapter 2 of On-Set Safety Protocols.",
    body: `<p>On professional sets, the safety meeting is a legal and contractual ritual — the 1st AD gathers the crew and walks through the day's hazards before a single frame is shot. It exists because it works: study after study of on-set incidents comes back to the same root cause, which is that nobody said the danger out loud. The stunt driver didn't know a crew member would be standing there. The grip didn't know the floor was wet. The safety meeting is how you close that gap, and it costs you two minutes.</p>

<p>Run it at the start of the day, and again any time the setup changes materially — a new location, a stunt, a special effect, a night move. Keep it short and specific. This isn't a lecture about being careful in general; it's a briefing about the <em>particular</em> hazards of <em>today</em>.</p>

<h2>What a good safety meeting covers</h2>

<p>Gather everyone — cast and crew, not just the department heads — and hit the concrete points. A useful briefing names the real hazards of the day and tells people exactly what to do about each one:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Today's specific hazards.</b> Stunts, weapons, vehicles, heights, water, fire, electrical loads — whatever is actually happening today, named plainly.</li>
  <li><b>The exclusion zones.</b> Where people may not stand, and who controls each zone (the stunt area, the camera-car path, the rigging overhead).</li>
  <li><b>The emergency plan.</b> Where the first-aid kit is, who the designated medic or first-aider is, and the location of the nearest hospital.</li>
  <li><b>How to stop.</b> Restate that anyone can call "hold" for safety, and what word to use so everyone hears it.</li>
  <li><b>Weather and environment.</b> Heat, cold, sun, terrain — and where the shade, water, and warm-up are.</li>
</ul>

<p>Then <strong>ask if anyone has a concern.</strong> Actually pause and wait. The whole point of Chapter 1's culture is that people feel able to answer — and the safety meeting is where you prove, every single day, that speaking up is welcome.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Almost every on-set incident traces back to one thing: nobody said the danger out loud. The safety meeting is how you say it — and it costs you two minutes a day.</div>

<h2>Build safety into the call sheet</h2>

<p>The safety meeting is the spoken version; the call sheet is the written one, and they should match. Every call sheet you send should carry a <strong>safety block</strong> — a few lines that make the plan permanent and reach the people who missed the huddle. At minimum it lists the nearest hospital with its address, the emergency and production contacts, the location of first aid, and a short note flagging the day's specific hazards ("Scene 14 involves a prop firearm — see firearms protocol; brief at 8am"). Putting it in writing does two things: it forces you to <em>think</em> about the day's risks in prep, and it gives you a documented record that the briefing happened. If the worst occurs, the difference between a defensible production and a negligent one is often exactly this paper trail. It takes ten minutes to add and it's the cheapest insurance you'll ever buy.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Before every shoot day, I look up the nearest emergency room to the location and put the real address and drive time on the call sheet — not "nearest hospital: TBD." The one time you need it, you will not have the composure to Google it. Do it in prep, when your hands are steady. On a remote location, also note where cell coverage actually works, because "call 911" is useless advice in a dead zone.</p>
</div>`,
