    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Film set etiquette can look like fussy old-fashioned ritual — the quiet, the call-and-response, the "who do I talk to?" But almost every piece of set protocol exists for a reason, and most of those reasons are safety. A well-run set isn't just polite. It's a set where information travels fast and nobody gets hurt by surprise.`,
    seoTitle: "Film Set Etiquette & the Chain of Command | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Film set etiquette and the chain of command as safety — set protocol, radio discipline, standard verbal warnings, and why a well-run set is a safe set. Chapter 3 of On-Set Safety Protocols.",
    body: `<p>New filmmakers often treat set etiquette as social hazing — a bunch of unwritten rules that exist to make newcomers feel out of place. It's the opposite. The protocols evolved on sets where real things were dangerous, and they're the accumulated wisdom of an industry figuring out how not to get people killed. When you understand the <em>why</em> behind the etiquette, it stops being fussy and starts being obviously sensible.</p>

<h2>The chain of command is a safety system</h2>

<p>On a film set, the director drives the creative vision, but the <strong>1st AD runs the floor</strong> — including safety. That single clear line of authority is what stops a set from descending into chaos, and chaos is where accidents live. When everyone knows who's in charge of the floor, information and instructions travel through a clean channel instead of a dozen people shouting over each other. On a micro-budget shoot you may not have a dedicated 1st AD, but <em>someone</em> must own that role: one person who calls the roll, controls the set, and has the authority to hold everything for safety.</p>

<p>The etiquette that flows from this is practical. You don't wander into another department's work area or move their gear, because they know its hazards and you don't — that stray cable you'd like to tidy might be feeding a 2K light. You don't give instructions to a department that isn't yours; you route it through the AD or the department head. This isn't about ego or hierarchy for its own sake. It's about making sure that the person who understands a given hazard is the person controlling it.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Set protocol looks like fussy ritual until you realize almost every rule is a safety rule in disguise. A well-run set is one where information travels fast and nobody is hurt by surprise.</div>

<h2>The verbal protocols that keep people safe</h2>

<p>A working set has a shared vocabulary of spoken warnings, and they exist purely so that a moving hazard is announced before it reaches someone who can't see it coming. Learn them and use them — they're the audible version of the safety-first culture:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>"Points!"</b> — Someone is carrying a long or sharp object (a light stand, a length of pipe) through a crowded space. Everyone stays clear of the ends.</li>
  <li><b>"Striking!"</b> — A light or object is about to be turned on, moved, or removed. Don't be startled, and mind the space.</li>
  <li><b>"Hot points!" / "Watch your backs!"</b> — Something is moving fast behind you or through the walkway. Make room now, ask later.</li>
  <li><b>"Eyes!"</b> — A bright light is about to hit; protect your vision and don't look directly at it.</li>
  <li><b>Radio discipline.</b> Keep channels clear for the people running the floor; safety and AD calls take priority over chatter.</li>
</ul>

<p>Underneath all of it is a simple attitude: <strong>stay aware, stay out of the way, and pass information up the chain.</strong> A quiet, orderly set isn't about formality. It's about a room full of people who can hear the warning that matters and know exactly who to tell when they spot a problem. That's what set etiquette actually buys you — and it's why the "polite" set and the "safe" set are the same set.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The fastest way to spot an amateur set isn't the gear — it's the noise. On a chaotic set, nobody knows who's in charge, three people give conflicting calls, and the warnings get lost in the crosstalk. That's exactly the environment where someone walks backward into a light stand or trips over a cable nobody announced. Establish one clear voice on the floor and a habit of calling the standard warnings, and you've quietly removed a whole category of accidents before lunch.</p>
</div>`,
