    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `"Everyone is responsible for safety" is true, and also a trap — because when everyone is responsible, it's easy for no one to be. This chapter draws the real map: who owns what, where the legal buck stops, and how responsibility is shared without becoming diffuse.`,
    seoTitle: "Who's Responsible for Safety on a Film Set | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Who is responsible for safety on a film set — the producer's duty of care, the 1st AD on the floor, department heads, the safety coordinator, and everyone's shared role. Chapter 4 of On-Set Safety Protocols.",
    body: `<p>Yes, everyone on set shares responsibility for safety — that's the culture we built in Chapter 1. But "shared responsibility" only works when it sits on top of <em>specific</em> responsibility. Someone has to legally own it, someone has to run it on the floor, and each department has to own its own hazards. Without that structure, "everyone's responsible" quietly becomes "nobody checked."</p>

<h2>The map of responsibility</h2>

<p>On any production, safety responsibility is layered. Understanding the layers tells you who to look to for what — and, if you're the one at the top, exactly how much sits on your shoulders:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The producer / production company — the legal buck.</b> As the employer, the production carries the ultimate duty of care to everyone it hires. This is where liability lands, which is why the producer must resource safety, not just wish for it.</li>
  <li><b>The 1st AD — safety on the floor.</b> The AD runs the set day-to-day and is the operational owner of safety: calling the safety meeting, controlling the set, and holding when needed.</li>
  <li><b>Department heads — their own hazards.</b> The gaffer owns electrical, the key grip owns rigging, the armorer owns weapons, the stunt coordinator owns stunts. Each is the expert on, and the controller of, their department's risks.</li>
  <li><b>The safety coordinator — the specialist.</b> For genuinely hazardous work (stunts, firearms, pyro), you bring in a dedicated professional whose only job that day is safety. On a small film, this is money well spent, not a luxury.</li>
  <li><b>Every crew member — eyes and a voice.</b> Everyone is responsible for working safely, watching for hazards, and speaking up. This is the shared layer that sits on top of the specific ones.</li>
</ul>

<p>The key insight is that these layers <strong>don't compete — they stack.</strong> The producer resourcing safety doesn't remove the AD's floor duty; the AD running the floor doesn't remove the gaffer's responsibility for their own cable runs. Each layer covers what the others can't see.</p>

<div class="pullquote">"Everyone is responsible for safety" only works when someone specific is too. Shared responsibility has to sit on top of clear ownership — or it becomes nobody's job.</div>

<h2>Duty of care is not optional — or transferable</h2>

<p>Here's the part low-budget producers most want to wish away: as the employer, you have a <strong>duty of care</strong> to the people you bring onto your set, and you can't sign it away. Making crew "volunteers" or "favors" doesn't erase your responsibility for their safety — if anything, unpaid and inexperienced crew need more protection, not less. Cutting the stunt coordinator to save money doesn't transfer the risk to someone else; it just means the risk is now being managed by someone unqualified, which is you. The honest way to think about it: if a hazard is beyond your team's competence, your job isn't to wing it, it's to either bring in the person who can do it safely or not shoot it. That decision — spend the money on the specialist, or change the shot — is one of the most important safety calls a producer makes, and it's covered hazard-by-hazard in the chapters ahead.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>When a day involves a real hazard — a stunt, a weapon, a fire effect — I name the person responsible for it out loud in the safety meeting: "For the car gag, Maria is the safety coordinator; her word is final, including mine." It does two things. It tells the crew exactly whose "stop" to obey instantly, and it stops the director (sometimes me) from overriding a safety call in the heat of the moment. Diffuse responsibility is dangerous. A name is safe.</p>
</div>`,
