    time: "9 min",
    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `Grip work is the physics department of a film set — heavy things held up in the air over people's heads. Most of it is simple, and all of it is safe if you follow one principle: assume everything wants to fall, and rig so it can't. Here's how to keep gear up and crew unhurt.`,
    seoTitle: "Grip, Rigging & Working at Heights: Set Safety | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Grip and rigging safety on a film set — stands, sandbags, overhead loads, ladders, and working safely at height. How to secure gear so nothing falls. Chapter 6 of On-Set Safety Protocols.",
    body: `<p>Grips exist to shape light and support the camera, and a huge part of that job is holding heavy objects steady — lights on tall stands, flags and overheads, camera on a jib. The failure mode is obvious and ugly: something up high comes down on someone below. The entire discipline of rigging safety is built around a single, slightly paranoid assumption that serves you well: <em>everything wants to fall, so rig it as if it will try.</em></p>

<h2>Keep it standing: the everyday rules</h2>

<p>Most grip safety is unglamorous habit, repeated until it's automatic. Get these right and the common accidents — a toppled light stand, a dropped flag, a stand walking off in the wind — simply stop happening:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Sandbag every stand.</b> Any stand holding weight or height gets sandbags on the legs — more weight up high means more bags down low. This is the number-one grip habit.</li>
  <li><b>Widest leg toward the weight.</b> Point a stand's tallest/widest leg under the direction of the load (the boom arm, the heavy head) so it can't tip that way.</li>
  <li><b>Safety the overheads.</b> Anything rigged above people gets a secondary safety — a cable or chain that catches it if the primary mount fails. No single point of failure over a person's head.</li>
  <li><b>Cap and cover.</b> Put tennis balls or caps on stand spikes at eye level; a stand top at head height is an eye injury waiting to happen.</li>
  <li><b>Mind the wind outdoors.</b> Wind turns a flag or overhead into a sail. Reduce the surface, add weight, and strike it before a gust does.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Working at height</h2>

<p>The other half of grip safety is people going up, not just gear. Ladders and platforms are where serious injuries happen because a fall from even modest height can be catastrophic. The rules are simple and non-negotiable: use the <strong>right ladder for the job</strong>, fully opened and on stable ground, and never stand on the top step or over-reach — move the ladder instead. Have someone <strong>foot the ladder</strong> (hold it steady) when anyone's up it. For anything beyond a standard ladder — scaffolding, a scissor lift, rigging into a ceiling, or work where a fall would be a long way down — you're into territory that needs proper fall protection and, often, a qualified rigger. Hanging a heavy light from a real structural point is not a "figure it out" job; if the point fails, the light lands on the cast. When the height or the load gets serious, that's the Chapter 4 call again: bring in the person who rigs for a living, or find a way to get the shot from the ground.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The whole discipline of rigging safety fits in one paranoid sentence: assume everything wants to fall, and rig it so it can't.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The sandbag is the most ignored piece of safety gear on a low-budget set, because bags are heavy, boring, and always somewhere else. So people "just this once" put a big light on a tall stand with no bags, on a set full of moving people. That's the shot where someone's elbow catches a leg and a fixture comes down. Make it a rule that no weighted stand goes up without bags, full stop — and keep the bags near the stands, not in a corner, so there's no excuse.</p>
</div>`,
