    desc: "Stunts, vehicles, fire, and special effects — when to bring in a pro",
    time: "9 min",
    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `Fights, falls, car moves, fire — the big-ticket action that pulls audiences in is also where an indie set is most likely to hurt someone. The rule that governs all of it is the same: nothing dangerous happens without a qualified coordinator, and everything is rehearsed cold before it's shot hot.`,
    seoTitle: "Stunts, Vehicles & Special Effects Safety | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Stunt, vehicle, and special-effects safety on set — the stunt coordinator, rehearsing and building up slowly, camera cars, fire and pyrotechnics, and when to fake it in camera or post. Chapter 8 of On-Set Safety Protocols.",
    body: `<p>Action is seductive, especially on a small film — a fight, a fall, a car screaming past camera feels like production value you can't afford any other way. But this is exactly the category where enthusiasm outruns competence and people get badly hurt. The good news is that the professionals have a method, and it isn't a secret: <strong>a qualified coordinator designs it, and you rehearse it slowly and completely before anyone does it at speed.</strong> Almost every stunt injury on an under-resourced set comes from skipping one of those two steps.</p>

<h2>The stunt coordinator and the build-up</h2>

<p>For any real physical action — a punch that connects, a fall, a push down stairs, anything with a vehicle — you bring in a <strong>stunt coordinator</strong>. That's not just for the celebrity performer's benefit; it's the person who knows how to make the hit look real while the bodies stay safe, and whose word on the day is final. Under them, the sacred process is the <strong>build-up</strong>: you walk the action at quarter speed, then half, then three-quarters, checking marks and safety at each stage, and only go full speed once every beat is known. You never "just try it" at full commitment on the first take. Here's the working checklist for anything in this category:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>A qualified coordinator runs it.</b> Stunt coordinator for action, a licensed effects/pyro tech for fire, a precision driver for vehicle work. Their stop is final.</li>
  <li><b>Rehearse cold, then build up.</b> Walk it slow, increase speed in stages, and shoot full-speed only when every mark and safety is locked.</li>
  <li><b>Use the trained performer.</b> Stunts are performed by people trained for them, not by your lead actor "giving it a go" or a keen crew member.</li>
  <li><b>Clear the zone and post a medic.</b> Define who is inside the action area (as few as possible) and have first aid immediately on hand.</li>
  <li><b>One shot at a time.</b> Reset fully between takes. Fatigue and rushing to "get one more" is where the build-up discipline breaks.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Vehicles, fire, and the case for faking it</h2>

<p>Two categories deserve their own warning. <strong>Vehicles</strong> are heavy, fast, and unforgiving: a car near camera and crew is a serious hazard, and any real driving action needs a precision driver, a locked-down zone, and often a picture car rigged so the "driver" isn't actually driving (a tow rig or process trailer). Never put an untrained actor behind the wheel for a driving shot with crew around. <strong>Fire and pyrotechnics</strong> are licensed-professional territory, full stop — flames, explosions, and smoke effects require a certified effects technician and usually permits, and are never a DIY experiment. And here's the liberating part: modern tools mean you rarely need the real thing. A punch sells on the reaction and the sound; a fireball is safer and often better as a practical small element enhanced in post, or fully in VFX; a car "crash" is angles, sound, and a locked stationary vehicle. The most experienced action directors are relentless about faking whatever can be faked, because the safest stunt is the one you didn't actually perform. This is the Chapter 4 principle at its sharpest — resource it with a pro, or design it so nobody's in danger.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The safest stunt is the one you didn't actually perform. Design it with a coordinator, rehearse it cold, and fake everything the camera and the edit will let you fake.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The most dangerous words on an indie action day are "let's just get it in one." Every stunt professional I've worked with does the opposite — they'll spend an hour walking a ten-second fight so slowly it looks silly, checking every contact and landing, before anyone throws a real-speed punch. That "boring" rehearsal is the entire safety system. When a director pushes to skip it to save time, that's precisely the moment to slow down, because the time you save by rushing an action beat is the time you'll lose to an ambulance.</p>
</div>`,
